04086nam a22006375i 9781442671003DE-B159720210824034702.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210824t20172003onc    fo  d z      eng d  a97814426710037 a10.3138/97814426710032doi  a(DE-B1597)483014  a(OCoLC)1004877810  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  aonccCA-ON 7aSOC0000002bisacsh04a302.23/451 aDoyle, Aaron, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aArresting Images :bCrime and Policing in Front of the Television Camera /cAaron Doyle. 1aToronto : bUniversity of Toronto Press, c[2017] 4cÂ©2003  a1 online resource (192 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tCHAPTER ONE. Introduction -- tCHAPTER TWO. Three Alternative Ways of Thinking about Television's Influences -- tCHAPTER THREE. Reality Television and Policing: The Case of Cops -- tCHAPTER FOUR. Surveillance Cameras, Amateur Video, and 'Real' Crime on Television -- tCHAPTER FIVE. Television and the Policing of Vancouver's Stanley Cup Riot -- tCHAPTER SIX. The Media Logic of Greenpeace -- tCHAPTER SEVEN. Conclusions -- tCHAPTER EIGHT. Postscript: Television and Theorizing the Evolution of Criminal Justice -- tNotes -- tWorks Cited -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWhile most research on television examines its impact on viewers, Arresting Images asks instead how TV influences what is in front of the camera, and how it reshapes other institutions as it broadcasts their activities. Aaron Doyle develops his argument with four studies of televised crime and policing: the popular American 'reality-TV' series Cops; the televising of surveillance footage and home video of crime and policing; footage of Vancouver's Stanley Cup riot; and the publicity-grabbing demonstrations of the environmental group Greenpeace. Each of these studies is of significant interest in its own right, but Doyle also uses them to make a broader argument rethinking television's impacts. The four studies show how televised activities tend to become more institutionally important, tightly managed, dramatic, simplified and fitted to society's dominant values. Powerful institutions, like the police, harness television for their own legitimation and surveillance purposes, often dictating which situations are televised, and usually producing 'authorized definitions' of the situations, which allow them to control the consequences. While these institutions invoke the notion that "seeing is believing" to reinforce their positions of dominance, the book argues that many observers and researchers have long overstated and misunderstood the role of TV's visual component in shaping its influences.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 4aDISCOUNT-B. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978144267100340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781442671003423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781442671003.jpg  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK